<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence on Local Government Procurement submitted by The Prince’s Trust</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from The Prince’s Trust (LPG 53)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overview: </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Prince’s Trust helps disadvantaged young people to get their lives on track. It supports 13 to 30 year-olds who are unemployed and those struggling at school and at risk of exclusion. Many of the young people helped by The Trust are in or leaving care, facing issues such as homelessness or mental health problems, or they have been in trouble with the law. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Trust’s programmes give vulnerable young people the practical and financial support needed to stabilise their lives, helping develop self-esteem and skills for work. The Trust supported 55,801 young people between April 2012 and March 2013. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Prince’s Trust Public Sector Team raises funds from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">government, local authority, lottery and other statutory sources. In England the Public Sector team is made up of 30 people who work in three areas:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The National Public Sector Team develops relationships with central government and leads on any bids with a national remit.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Each Region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(South, Central and North England) has Public Sector Teams developing local partnerships.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This work is supported by a Bid Writing and Resources Team. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2012/13 the Public Sectors Team’s raised £18 million and secured significant funds through Local Government Procurement. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The main points of The Prince’s Trust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> evidence are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Initiatives such as Passport PQQ’s and multiple Local Authority frameworks would increase efficiencies for Local Authorities and suppliers, whilst also encouraging the involvement of smaller organisations. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local Authority staff are considered accessible and long term relationships have been developed that have withstood change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘Meet the buyer’ events and opportunities to meet Commissioners and other suppliers are welcomed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Further information under the topics suggested by the Committee is detailed below:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent is local government procurement organised to deliver value for money and social, economic and environmental objectives, including stimulating the local economy? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Do Local Authorities harness the power of the voluntary sector to involve local residents, philanthropy, corporate or charitable funding in their procurement?  Some solutions to their perceived problems are too narrowly specified to enable creative or good value solutions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Largely Commissioners are accessible and invite a wide enough cross section of partners to the table when exploring solutions to problems. In defence of Local Authorities, it must be incredibly hard to get a co-ordinated and cohesive voice from the wider sector – this is where local C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommunity and Voluntary Service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s can be helpful on occasions by acting as a conduit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The requirement to fund new ‘innovative’ solutions is often difficult for organisations (particularly third sector ones who may not have a lot of resource and flexibility) to respond to, particularly when they have proven track records of programmes that work and consistently deliver result to an identified local need.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Is this the best way of assessing delivery?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Passport PQQ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would save organisations having </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to do individual PQQs for each Local A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthority. The idea is reflected here: </span><a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/pressroom/content/20110926IPR27495/html/Public-procurement-passport-could-make-it-easier-for-small-firms-to-bid"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.europarl.europ</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">a</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.eu/news/en/pressroom/content/20110926IPR27495/html/Public-procurement-passport-could-make-it-easier-for-small-firms-to-bid</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Could evidence of quality marks substitute questions or allow organisations to move onto the next section? For example a Pre tender Questionnaire published by Rotherham Borough Council allowed organisations to skip questions under sections such as The Environment if they could supply a certificate for an Environmental Management System </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(such as ISO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1400).  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are local authorities able to develop long-term relationships with contractors?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In general Local Authorities have developed long term relationships with The Prince’s Trust, even when significant changes have taken place. It is incumbent upon both parties to ensure that relationships can withstand organisational change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the current climate, where there are still significant changes taking place within Local Authorities, key personnel can, and have, often changed, resulting in new relationships having to be formed and historic events re-visited to ensure clarity. Do Local Authorities use any form of partnership Customer Relationship Management that they update on a regular basis?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Multi Local Authority Frameworks would increase efficiencies for Local Authorities and suppliers for example Manchester City Council Troubled Families Supplier Framework can be used by 22 North West Local Authorities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is beginning to happen in some areas, for example in South Yorkshire, West Yorkshire and the North East Local Authorities worked together to bid for 2013-15 ESF NEET funding. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How can local authorities access the skills, expertise and capabilities to implement effective procurement strategies, including value for money and social and economic objectives?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">More specifically, does local government have sufficient understanding of its procurement expenditure and the markets for goods and services to deliver quality procurement strategies—locally and regionally. If not, how can deficiencies be addressed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘Meet the buyer’ events would help Local Authorities to develop their strategy, understand local businesses and organisations and develop c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ost effective partnerships. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o make ‘Meet the Funder’ events more useful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in addition to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> going through bid documents, there could be a networking session </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for suppliers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">before or after.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as ‘Meet the buyer events’, commissioners could support providers to identify and form partnerships with other providers, particularly as for many services there is often just one contract available. Commissioners often favour partnership bids but, given the timescales, providers often have problems developing effective partnerships and submitting partnership bids. A previous example of how this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could be improved is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Lambeth Borough Council C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hildren and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oung </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ervice Commissioning team</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> introduced a number of current providers via email and offered to host </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introductory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meetings. This was to support smaller groups who were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduce them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">selves to larger organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The voluntary and community sector could support C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommissioners with access to their projects and programmes or link them into elected members who visit community projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This would support Local Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in bringing policy and procurement ‘to life’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica 45 Light'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>